// Sections match URANUS_SCROLL_PATH waypoints in PlanetScrollCameras.ts.

const items = [
  {
    id:       'aftertouch',
    category: 'CONCEPT',
    title:    'Aftertouch',
    meta:     'Haptic UI · Prototype',
    body: [
      'Aftertouch asks what a UI feels like if pressure, not just position, is an input — a button that registers how hard it was pressed and responds differently to a tap versus a held, firm press. Most touch interfaces treat every tap as identical; this one does not.',
      'If it had a brief: a media-player scrub bar where press pressure controls scrub speed, or a messaging app where a firm press on send triggers a "this is urgent" flag instead of a separate UI control. The distance from speculative to real is short — the Web Pressure/Force Touch APIs already exist on some devices, they are just almost never used for anything beyond a context menu.',
      'What it reveals: an ongoing interest in inputs that go unused by default. Most interface work optimises the visual layer; this one is about optimising the layer underneath the finger.',
    ],
    topics: ['The Question', 'If It Had a Brief', 'What It Reveals'],
  },
  {
    id:       'palimpsest',
    category: 'CONCEPT',
    title:    'Palimpsest',
    meta:     'Interaction Design · Early sketch',
    body: [
      'Palimpsest is a UI direction for collaborative documents where every edit stays visible as a fading layer underneath the current text, instead of being erased or hidden behind a version-history modal — the document\'s own history becomes part of its visual texture, like an actual palimpsest.',
      'The origin: frustration with how invisible collaborative editing history usually is. Google Docs\' version history exists but is a separate view nobody opens; the interesting question was whether the history could live in the same view as the document, at low enough opacity to not distract.',
      'Status: an early Figma sketch and a rough CSS proof-of-concept for the fade-layer effect, nothing built into a working editor yet. Waiting on the right small project to actually test it against real collaborative editing, not a static mockup.',
    ],
    topics: ['The Direction', 'The Origin', 'Current Status'],
  },
  {
    id:       'weathervane',
    category: 'CONCEPT',
    title:    'Weathervane',
    meta:     'Data Sonification · Concept',
    body: [
      'Weathervane turns a live data stream — server error rates, in this concept — into ambient sound rather than a dashboard graph, so a developer working nearby can sense a problem building before they would ever glance at a monitor. One sentence: dashboards you hear, not just see.',
      'The single blocking constraint: making the sound genuinely ambient rather than annoying is a sound-design problem, not an engineering one, and sound design at that level of subtlety is outside current expertise. If that constraint disappeared — a collaborator with real audio-design chops — this moves from concept to prototype fast.',
      'Currently exists as a written concept brief and a rough Web Audio API proof-of-concept mapping a mock error-rate feed to pitch and rhythm — not yet something a listener would describe as pleasant.',
    ],
    topics: ['The Idea', 'The Blocking Constraint', 'Its Current Form'],
  },
  {
    id:       'nocturne',
    category: 'CONCEPT',
    title:    'Nocturne',
    meta:     'Design Fiction · WIP',
    body: [
      'Nocturne is the sketchbook entry: a screen-free bedtime interface concept — a physical dial and ambient light instead of a phone app, for the specific job of winding down a nighttime routine without the blue-light, notification-laden problem a phone brings into the process. Not committed to yet, and deliberately unfinished here.',
      'What makes it different from the rest: everything else in this section is a software interaction pattern. This one is physical-object-first, softer in scope, and closer to product design than interface design — the point of this section is to show that range exists, not just repeat the same kind of concept four times.',
      'The missing piece is genuinely hardware: an industrial designer or a hardware prototyper who could take the physical-dial idea past a cardboard mockup. If that person is reading this, Neptune is where the conversation starts.',
    ],
    topics: ['The Sketchbook', 'Showing Range', 'The Right Collaborator'],
  },
];
